When they made this game the intent was to pay homage to giant monster movies hence George (King Kong) and Lizzy (Godzilla). Since it was a 3 player game they needed a third character so they made a giant Wolfman since he was the only one of the classic human sized monsters that was an animal (Dracula, Frankenstein, Mummy). The film is set in Chicago because the company that made the game was based in Illinois. In the game they were humans that were mutated into giant anthropomorphic animals. While all fun and good, I completely forgot about the game until the trailer for the movie, and in doing so, remembered the core aspect of the game, you and your friends, because let‚Äôs face it, the single player was shite, destroy, or rampage, see what I did there, aren‚Äôt I oh so clever, through various cities, fighting the army, and faffing around with your older siblings for one glorious moment where you are the gorilla, and he is the underpowered wolf, who is inferior in all ways. You achieve this moment of bliss right before he whacks you on your head, and picks you upside down, being drawn out of any sense of enjoyment you once had. Now this movie looks nothing like the game it was based off of, and in my opinion, and this could just be the blood rushing down to my brain, but I feel like I‚Äôd much rather see two giant fuck-off monsters battling, bathing in the visceral carnage of the city, and playing around with tanks as if they were your mom‚Äôs special toys.

Comment:
This kinda reminds me of one of my favorite SNES video games back in the 90s called Primal Rage.
It's a fighting game of dinosaurs and other creatures who were awoken when a meteor hit the world, but there are still humans living, the world then is named Urth and the humans have all been divided into 7 clan, each one treating each monster as their god. So the gameplay of primal rage is that these 7 monsters are fighting each other to see who will rule the world. And for some strange reason this trailer kinda reminds me of the game, since both this movie and the game has these gorilla characters, and there are more monsters that are gonna like fight each other. Another huge difference is that the humans from the movie are the ones who will also fight against the giant animal mutants. I really find this movie interesting! I may possibly watch it when it comes out on dvd. Sometimes i really wish there was an actual Primal Rage movie! That would be great! ^^

So, lemme get this straight:

RAMPAGE: A Midway arcade classic arcade game (and one of my personal favorites) is finally getting to the big screen.

I have a few questions here:

1. Who was the person who decided that this particular arcade game should be one of the first to have a stand alone movie, rather than PAC-MAN, DIG-DUG, GALAGA, or even DONKEY KONG for that matter? Does Sony own the copyrights to those games being that they were mentioned in that horrible ‚ÄúPixels‚Äù? Or is it more like a dart board kinda scenario? Like the director of this movie LITERALLY blindfolded themselves and just threw a dart at a board that said ‚ÄúCLASSIC ARCADE GAME MOVIE IDEAS‚Äù. Discuss.

2. I understand that adaptations from video games to movies must have SOME changes, I get that. But they couldn‚Äôt even stick with the one key material that the monsters were all originally human that turned into monsters? Why does it have to be animals? Don‚Äôt get me wrong, I have nothing against it, I‚Äôm just curious.

3. I‚Äôm not saying Dwayne is a bad actor, but I feel like they could‚Äôve done better with the lead casting roll. In my personal opinion, I just feel as if Dwayne is a little. . .i dunno, a little overused I guess? He‚Äôs a mediocre actor at best, and I just feel like they‚Äôre kinda wearing him out. Again, that‚Äôs just my opinion.

But overall, I see a plus and minus in just this trailer alone.

The +: The parts with George and Ralph (Ralph is the wolf‚Äôs name btw) destroying through the town looked pretty cool and promising. Even with the little hint at Lizzie (the LIZZARD, not a croc) at the end. My favorite part overall of the original game was having monsters wreak havoc across cities as brothers in arms, rather than enimies. Imagine if King Kong and Godzilla teamed up to fight an even greater enemy than themselves? That sounds like an awesome idea if you ask me.

The -: The story revolving around Dwayne and the other human characters. Here‚Äôs the thing you must remember; the game Rampage has a very simple plot:

- 3 ordinary people get turned into monsters, and now wreak havoc all across the world. That‚Äôs basically about it.

Boom, that‚Äôs it. It‚Äôs not too complex, and not really that hard to follow. SO DONT TRY TO MAKE SOME COMPLEX RIDICULOUS BULLSHIT STORY THAT HAS NOTHING TO DO WITH THE MONSTERS, BUT THE HUMANS THAT HAVE TO STOP THEM.

I came here to see MONSTERS DESTROY THINGS AND EAT PEOPLE. AND SOMETIMES FLY ON PLANES AND VOMIT ON EACH OTHER (Play the Rampage N64 version, quality shit right there). But you get what I‚Äôm trying to say. GIVE US WHAT THE GAME WAS GLORIOUS FOR. 

Overall: As far as it looks now with just one trailer, it‚Äôs a 50/50 chance that I might try to go see it. I saw Pixels, and I regretting it after Cuburt was SPEAKING FUCKING ENGLISH.

Please, don‚Äôt go that direction, I beg you.

Comment:
This does look good, but...
I really wish they stuck to the source material of the game instead.
If people don't know, Rampage (a 1980's game) was based on 3 types of monsters who terrorized cities and ate people.  The goal was to do a certain percentage of damage by knocking down buildings while trying not to take damage from the military, from each other or from falling.  The monsters, a gorilla, a werewolf and a lizard (like Godzilla) were 100 foot tall beasts.  But these monsters were genetically altered humans.  The gorilla and the lizard were guys but the werewolf was a lady.
So even though it's looking interesting, it doesn't stick to the original concept.  Kind of bums me out a little.

Comment:
As a fan of the Rampage games this looks pretty disappointing. First off, they were humans who worked for a company who's chemicals ended up turning them into giant creatures  George the Gorilla, Ralph the Wolf, and Lizzie the Lizard. Their goal other than destroying everything was to get revenge on the evil company that did it to them. The arcade and N64 games were pretty amazing, but the sequel to those was a real let down, and eventually Midway shut down and their IP's were bought by Warner Bros. 

The graphics in the games had them as pretty animated and cartoony in a twisted dark sort of way, so to see them made all realistic for hollywood with a focus on The Rock vs the focus being on the monsters, is pretty disappointing.

Title: RAMPAGE - OFFICIAL TRAILER 1 [HD]
Comment:
Alright, here's my initial impressions: First, they're clearly taking this WAY too seriously, and second, why they gotta screw up the central concept every time they put the Rock in a video game movie?  First they make Doom about a nonsense genetic virus instead of a demon invasion, then they make Jumanji a video game instead of a board game, and now this.

Rampage was about PEOPLE who had been mutated into giant monsters.  The Hell kind of adaptation is this if there isn't going to be a scene when the monsters are defeated and they shrink back down into naked folks shuffling away while awkwardly covering themselves?  That was the most memorable part of the whole game!  It's not like there was much of a plot in the first place, but they couldn't even preserve that tiny little shred of a story thread?  Yeah, I shouldn't really care, but I played this game as a little kid, and I was kind of enthusiastic about this.  And this just seems... so... generic.

Seems to me this should've been a Wreck-It Ralph style animated feature about three people who get turned into monsters and go on the run while trying to control their urge to smash buildings.  They could've had the monsters talk, tell some dumb jokes, sold some dolls, made a new game, everybody wins.  But no, we get a cookie-cutter big monster disaster film that looks like something the SyFy channel cooked up.

Well, maybe it'll be good.  It's highly doubtful, but who knows?  It could still be a breakout hit.  And who knows, maybe the weaselly government guy is going to turn into the lizard monster.  Or was the lizard a woman?  Well, whatever.  That could be kind of... something.  I guess.

Maybe I'm aiming high.
